'''Conor McNicholas''' is a British journalist and editor. He formerly edited ''[[Top Gear (magazine)|Top Gear]]'' and [[IPC Media|IPC]]-run music magazine, ''[[New Musical Express]]'' (NME).

==Career==
His first professional post on a magazine was on a fledgling Manchester publication called ''Sub'', where he wrote a spoof horoscope under the pen name of Snufkin. After a period working on various magazines for [[Dennis Publishing]], McNicholas went on to write for the dance press holding senior positions at both ''Ministry'' and ''[[Mixmag]]'' magazines before going on to edit ''[[Muzik]]''. {{citation needed|date=September 2014}}

McNicholas served as editor of ''New Musical Express'' from 2003 to 2009. At the start of his term at ''NME'' he boosted sales by focusing on the 'new rock revolution' which included bands such as [[The Strokes]] and [[White Stripes]].{{citation needed|date=September 2014}}

In 2007, [[Morrissey]] announced that he was going to sue both McNicholas and ''NME'' for libel over an article on the singer's views on immigration.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7118412.stm|work=BBC News|title=Morrissey to sue NME over story|date=29 November 2007|accessdate=30 April 2010}}</ref> The case was settled in June 2012 when NME issued a statement saying \we apologise to Morrissey if he or anyone else misunderstood our piece\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-18410933|work=BBC News|title=NME apologises to singer Morrissey over article|date=13 June 2012|accessdate=30 April 2010}}</ref>

